# =============================================================================
# Model: gemma4:26b_opencode_no_think
# Base:  gemma4:26b (25.8B, Q4_K_M, vision + tools + thinking)
# GPU:   Tesla P40, 23040 MiB VRAM
# Built: 2026-05-02
#
# EVALUATION VERDICT: HIGHLY RECOMMENDED
# ---------------------------------------
# Gemma4:26b is the best-performing model tested in this suite for opencode:
#   - Highest VRAM ceiling (77824 tokens vs 49152 for qwen3-coder, 43520 for GLM)
#   - Clean tool calling: 5/5 runs had empty content alongside tool calls with
#     no system instruction needed — better out-of-the-box than other models
#   - Correct multi-turn tool result handling
#   - No visible thinking blocks (PARSER strips them internally)
#   - Vision capability as a bonus for multimodal tasks
#
# NOTE ON "no_think" SUFFIX
# -------------------------
# Gemma4 does not have a /no_think toggle like Qwen3. Its thinking is handled
# entirely by the RENDERER/PARSER — <think> blocks are generated and stripped
# internally, never visible to the client. The suffix signals the same intent
# (fast, direct tool use) for naming consistency with the other variants.
#
# CHANGES FROM BASE gemma4:26b
# ----------------------------
# 1. num_ctx 77824
#    Base has no num_ctx set (ollama defaults to 2048 — too small for opencode).
#    77824 is the exact VRAM ceiling on P40: ~44 tok/s fully in VRAM.
#    The cliff falls between 77824 and 78848.
#
# 2. temperature 1 — kept unchanged
#    Tool call JSON was 5/5 clean at temperature=1. No benefit in reducing it.
#
# 3. SYSTEM — explicit empty-content instruction
#    Tool calls were already clean at temp=1, but the instruction is added as
#    a safety net consistent with other opencode variants in this suite.
#
# BENCHMARK — Tesla P40, 2026-05-02
# ----------------------------------
# Generation speed sweep (num_predict=200, short prompt):
#
#   num_ctx   gen tok/s   prompt tok/s   notes
